chology, the contributors argue that in fact body hair plays a central role in constructing masculinity and femininity and sexual and cultural identities. It is sure to provide many academic researchers with a completely fresh perspective on all of the fields mentioned above.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBody hairxSocial aspects. 0aBody image in women. 0aHairxSocial aspects. 4aLiterature Studies 2020. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aWestern culture.  abeautification.  abody hair.  afemininity.  afetishistic pornography.  ahair removal.  ahairy women.  ahirsutism.  anatural female body.  awomen.1 aCaselli, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCocks, Neil, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD. Williams, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazú, Jacqueline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLesnik-Oberstein, Karin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLesnik-Oberstein, Karín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMacdonald, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScuriatti, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomson, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTondeur, Louise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVelasco, Sherry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalsh, Sue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779444440uhttps: